{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5bea4e64-37a5-4d23-b679-535c1880bab5","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (if you need one for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited        # enable core dumps in the current shell\n./YourApp                   # reproduce the crash\n# core file appears at /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\n> Note: `/cores/` must exist and be writable, and SIP must allow core dumps. You may need `sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"404f0fc6-1121-4453-8917-5cc0b48f65d7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no code changes needed.","outputTokens":313},"id":"be96c47a-80c7-4013-bec5-cadd2c08ad39","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:54:36.198Z","parentId":"b49f7eeb-1aaa-4344-b892-e7d5aaa7560b"}
